│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash happens due to a malformed PHI in the vectorized loop: the vector   │
│ recurrence PHI has an incoming value from the block it resides in ("[         │
│ %broadcast.splat2, %vector.body ]"), which violates dominance constraints.    │
│ Specifically, for a PHI, each incoming value must be defined in the           │
│ corresponding predecessor block of the PHI’s block. Having the PHI's own      │
│ block in the incoming list is only correct if the backedge comes from a       │
│ distinct predecessor latch, not the header itself.                            │
│                                                                               │
│ In the reproducer, the scalar recurrence is degenerate: %for = phi [          │
│ %for.start, %entry ], [ %for.next, %loop ] and %for.next = and i8 %for.start, │
│ -1. This simplifies to %for.start for both incoming edges after               │
│ SROA/instcombine-like reasoning. The vectorizer’s recurrence handling assumes │
│ a non-degenerate recurrence and places the "broadcast" (of the start value)   │
│ in the wrong block when it turns the recurrence into a                        │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePhi. The broadcast ends up in the header (%vector.body) │
│ and is used as the PHI’s backedge incoming value from that same block,        │
│ breaking dominance.                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - SCEV classifies %for and %for.next as invariant (%for.start). This implies  │
│ there is no true recurrence.                                                  │
│ - The error shows: "%broadcast.splat2 = shufflevector ..." and "%vector.recur │
│ = phi <4 x i8> ... [ %vector.recur.init, %vector.ph ], [ %broadcast.splat2,   │
│ %vector.body ]". The incoming from %vector.ph (the preheader) is fine. The    │
│ incoming from %vector.body (the header) is not: the value must be defined in  │
│ the predecessor latch block, not the header. Thus, the broadcast was          │
│ sunk/placed in the wrong block, or the PHI was wired to the wrong             │
│ predecessor.                                                                  │
│ - The assertion in processLoop verifies the whole function after              │
│ vectorization. The location indicates the error is introduced during VPlan    │
│ execution (LVP.executePlan), specifically during recipe placement/sinking.    │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The VPlan builder/transformer does not detect that the "recurrence" is a      │
│ degenerate case with identical incoming values after simplification. It still │
│ constructs a VPFirstOrderRecurrencePhi and a broadcast of the start value,    │
│ but sinks/emits the broadcast in the vector loop header (%vector.body) and    │
│ connects it as the backedge incoming to the PHI from %vector.body, instead of │
│ from the latch block. Under normal circumstances, the backedge incoming       │
│ should come from the latch predecessor, and any broadcast needed on the       │
│ backedge must be placed in that latch block or earlier, so that it dominates  │
│ the terminator of the predecessor.                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ This misplacement likely comes from one of:                                   │
│ - VPWidenPHIRecipe::executeImpl creating the backedge incoming using a value  │
│ built in the header builder rather than latch builder.                        │
│ - A VPlan transform (like sinkScalarOperands() or canonicalization) choosing  │
│ an invalid sink target for a dead instruction/broadcast in degenerate         │
│ recurrences and placing it into the header block (%vector.body) as a          │
│ convenience.                                                                  │
│ - Wiring of blocks in VPlan where the incoming from the backedge is recorded  │
│ as coming from the header instead of the latch, when the recurrence           │
│ simplifies.                                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ Given the symptom text and typical code structure, the fix is to ensure: (a)  │
│ degenerate recurrences are treated as invariants (no                          │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePhi), or (b) the broadcast used as backedge incoming is │
│ placed in and taken from the latch predecessor, not the header.               │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - VPlan.h: add explicit handling for degenerate recurrences flagged in        │
│ recipes.                                                                      │
│ - VPlanTransforms.cpp: in transforms that sink broadcasts or dead             │
│ instructions (e.g., sinkScalarOperands or related), ensure the sink target    │
│ for values feeding PHIs is the latch predecessor, not the header, and detect  │
│ degenerate recurrences to drop the recurrence.                                │
│ - VPlanRecipes.cpp: in VPWidenPHIRecipe::executeImpl (and possibly            │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::execute), fix the builder placement of the   │
│ backedge incoming value. Emit the broadcast in the latch builder, and wire    │
│ the PHI's incoming from the latch block. Additionally, if both incoming       │
│ values of the scalar PHI are identical and invariant, convert the recurrence  │
│ into a simple invariant broadcast in the preheader and avoid creating         │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePhi.                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Concretely:                                                                   │
│ (a) In VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::execute:                              │
│ - Before building the broadcast/recurrence, check if the scalar incoming      │
│ values are identical and invariant (LoopVectorizationLegality or SCEV can     │
│ expose this). If so, do not create a recurrence; create a single broadcast in │
│ the vector preheader and use it directly.                                     │
│ (b) When building the backedge incoming for recurrence PHIs:                  │
│ - Ensure the value comes from the latch block builder (LB.getLatchBuilder()   │
│ or the builder tied to the vector loop’s latch) and setIncoming from that     │
│ predecessor, not the header. Never use the header (%vector.body) as the       │
│ incoming block.                                                               │
│ (c) In any sinking utility in VPlanTransforms that moves broadcasts/dead      │
│ instructions, forbid sinking into the header if the value feeds a PHI’s       │
│ backedge; use the latch or preheader accordingly.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit points:                                                                  │
│ 1. llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.h (add flags/helpers to detect         │
│ degenerate recurrence in recipes)                                             │
│ 2. llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanTransforms.cpp (adjust sink target      │
│ selection and detect degenerate recurrence to drop it)                        │
│ 3. llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp (fix                        │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe and VPWidenPHIRecipe execution to place       │
│ backedge incoming in latch and convert degenerate recurrence to invariant     │
│ broadcast)                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash stems from constructing a vector recurrence PHI where the incoming  │
│ from the backedge is taken from the header block (%vector.body), violating    │
│ dominance. This is triggered by a degenerate scalar recurrence where both     │
│ incoming values are the same invariant, after simplification. The fix is to   │
│ either fold the recurrence to an invariant broadcast in the preheader, or     │
│ ensure the broadcast feeding the backedge is emitted in the latch predecessor │
│ and wired from that block. Updating VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe execution │
│ and associated sinking/canonicalization to respect predecessor placement will │
│ prevent forming invalid PHIs, fixing the assertion. The expected effect is    │
│ correct dominance and no verifier failure at the end of processLoop.          │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
